          "body": "The chapter's most theologically loaded moment is easy to miss: verses 6-7 record that the descendants of Ehud, themselves heads of fathers' households in Geba, were carried into exile to Manahath. The Chronicler does not explain this displacement or assign blame. What he does is register it — include it in the official genealogical record, name the exiled (Naaman, Ahijah, Gera), and then continue the lineage. For the post-exilic community reading Chronicles after seventy years of Babylonian captivity, this note is pastoral. Exile does not erase a family from God's record. The register keeps going after Manahath just as it kept going after Babylon. God's genealogical memory is not interrupted by geopolitical catastrophe. This is precisely the comfort the Chronicler offers a community that feared its own identity had been dissolved by the exile."
