        "range": "8:1-7",
        "excerpt": "And Benjamin became the father of Bela his firstborn... These are the sons of Ehud: these are the heads of fathers' households of the inhabitants of Geba, and they carried them into exile to Manahath.",
        "body": "The chapter opens at the patriarchal moment — Benjamin's five sons listed in birth order. This is the same list that appears in Genesis 46:21, though with significant differences in the names (the genealogical traditions for Benjamin are notoriously complex across Genesis, Numbers 26, and Chronicles). The Chronicler is not concerned with harmonizing these traditions; he is concerned with establishing Benjamin's tribal legitimacy by anchoring it in the generation of the patriarchs.\n\nVerse 6 introduces Ehud — almost certainly the judge of Judges 3:15 who delivered Israel from Moab. The Chronicler identifies his descendants as heads of fathers' households in Geba, certifying that the judge's line was a recognized leadership family. What follows is unexpected: they were exiled to Manahath. The passive verb galah (to be exiled, to be uncovered) is the same word used repeatedly for the Babylonian deportation (2 Kings 17:23; 25:21; Jeremiah 52:27). The Chronicler is not anachronistically projecting Babylon onto a pre-monarchic displacement — he is using the language his readers know for catastrophic removal from the land and applying it to Benjamin's tribal history, showing that displacement is not a new phenomenon. God's covenant register survived earlier exiles just as it survived Babylon.\n\nThe naming of the exiled individuals — Naaman, Ahijah, and Gera — is pastorally significant. These are not statistics. They are named people, enrolled in the official genealogy, whose exile is acknowledged but not treated as genealogical death. The register continues. This is the Chronicler's answer to the post-exilic anxiety: the exile did not break the line, and neither did the Babylonian captivity.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Galah* (8:6, 7) — the standard term for deportation/exile in the prophetic literature. *Rosh* (8:6) — head, leader; the same term used of tribal princes in Numbers. Its appearance here certifies the Ehud clan as authoritative before and after their displacement."
