        "excerpt": "Shaharaim became the father of children in the country of Moab after he had sent away Hushim and Baara his wives.",
        "body": "The Shaharaim episode (8:8-11) is the chapter's most theologically uncomfortable passage. A Benjaminite man is in Moab — we are not told why — has dismissed two wives, married a third (Hodesh), and is fathering children on foreign soil. The Chronicler includes this without comment. Some commentators (Sara Japhet, *I and II Chronicles*, 1993) have suggested Shaharaim's situation reflects the realities of the pre-monarchic period when Israelite families dispersed widely for economic and military reasons. Others see an echo of the Ruth narrative's framework: covenant families surviving and multiplying in Moab before return.\n\nWhat the Chronicler emphasizes is not the moral complexity but the genealogical outcome. The sons by Hodesh become \"heads of fathers' households\" (8:10) — legitimate clan leaders. The sons by Hushim (8:11) continue a further productive line. Elpaal's sons, named in 8:12, include Shemed, who built Ono and Lod. The genealogical argument is clear: irregularity of origin does not disqualify from Benjaminite identity if the lineage is real and the clan leadership is recognized.\n\nFor the Chronicler's audience — the post-exilic community that had itself survived seventy years in Babylon, married foreign women (Ezra 9-10 shows how common this was), and was now arguing about who belonged to the restored community — this passage is not a parenthesis. It is a mirror. The tribal register has always included complicated families. The question is not the purity of origin but the continuity of the covenant line.\n\nVerse 12's construction notice (Shemed built Ono and Lod) anchors Shaharaim's descendants in identifiable, recoverable territory. These towns appear in the post-exilic lists (Nehemiah 11:35), meaning the Chronicler's genealogy is simultaneously a land title — these western towns belong to Benjamin because a Benjaminite built them."
