        "range": "8:13-28",
        "excerpt": "Beriah and Shema, who were heads of fathers' households of the inhabitants of Aijalon, who put to flight the inhabitants of Gath... These were heads of the fathers' households according to their generations, chief men who lived in Jerusalem.",
        "body": "The long middle section of the chapter (8:13-28) traces six generations of Elpaal's descendants through a series of named sub-lists. The sheer density of names is often treated as a problem for the reader, but it is the Chronicler's point: Benjamin's leadership families are numerous, documented, and specific. The post-exilic community was not reconstructing a tribe from mythology; it was recovering a historically attested, meticulously registered lineage.\n\nThe two action-notices embedded in this section are strategically placed. The military notice of verse 13 — Beriah and Shema drove out the inhabitants of Gath from Aijalon — establishes Benjaminite military precedent in the western valleys. The Aijalon Valley was a strategic corridor between the coastal plain and the Judean hills; control of it mattered militarily and economically. That Benjaminites expelled Philistines from it is the Chronicler's way of saying: this tribe was not merely a survivor — it was a territorial power.\n\nThe summary formula of verse 28 is the chapter's first major structural close: \"These were heads of the fathers' households according to their generations, chief men who lived in Jerusalem.\" The word *toledah* (generations, genealogies) is the technical term for official genealogical record — the same word used in Genesis for the structured accounts of patriarchal families. Its appearance here certifies the entire preceding register as official and authoritative. And the phrase \"who lived in Jerusalem\" is the post-exilic reader's passport: these are your ancestors, and they lived in the city you are rebuilding. You belong here.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Toledah* (8:28) — from *yalad* (to beget); the technical genealogical term, used in Genesis for the \"account of\" each patriarchal family. *Yerushalaim* (8:28) — the holy city; its appearance at the chapter's midpoint structural close is the Chronicler's way of declaring that the whole preceding genealogy converges on Jerusalem."
