        "excerpt": "Ner became the father of Kish, and Kish became the father of Saul, and Saul became the father of Jonathan, Malchi-shua, Abinadab and Eshbaal.",
        "body": "The chapter's final movement is its reason for being. Everything from 8:1-28 has been preparation; 8:29-40 is the destination. The Chronicler traces Saul's line from Jeiel, father of Gibeon (8:29), through Ner-Kish-Saul (8:33) and then nine more generations to Azel's six sons (8:38) and Ulam's 150 warrior-descendants (8:40). This is the most meticulous genealogical passage in the entire Benjaminite section.\n\nThe pivot verse is 8:33. Three rapid *yalad* (begat) clauses — Ner begat Kish, Kish begat Saul, Saul begat four sons — compress the pre-monarchic and early monarchic periods into a single breath, then slow down. Saul's four sons are named: Jonathan, Malchi-shua, Abinadab, and Eshbaal (the latter called Ish-bosheth in Samuel, where the Baal element is suppressed). The Chronicler uses the original name — Eshbaal — without apology, consistent with his practice of historical fidelity over theological sanitizing.\n\nVerse 34 is theologically charged: Jonathan's son was Merib-baal (= Mephibosheth of 2 Samuel 9). The Chronicler's inclusion of Merib-baal is not genealogical accident. Merib-baal is the living embodiment of David's covenant loyalty to Jonathan (2 Samuel 9:1-7) — the man David restored \"for the sake of your father Jonathan.\" In including Merib-baal and tracing his descendants nine more generations, the Chronicler is quietly acknowledging that David's kindness to Jonathan's house was historically real and genealogically consequential. The line that David spared continued.\n\nThe chapter closes with Ulam's 150 warrior-descendants (8:40). The number 150 is not symbolic (unlike the 144,000 of Revelation or the 70 of the Sanhedrin tradition); it is specific and historical. The Chronicler is certifying that the house of Saul, far from disappearing after the Davidic transition, multiplied into a militarily significant clan. For the post-exilic community, the pastoral implication is clear: if God preserved and multiplied the very dynasty He judged, how much more will He preserve and multiply the dynasty He chose?\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yalad* appears three times in 8:33 alone — the repetition is deliberate pacing, slowing the reader at the moment of maximum genealogical significance. *Gibbor chayil* (8:40, mighty man of valor) — the Chronicler's standard epithet for elite warriors (cf. 1 Chronicles 5:24; 7:2, 7, 11). *Darakh* (8:40, archers — literally \"those who bend the bow\") — the precise military specialty, not a generic term for soldiers."
